<TITLE> Government wants IPL dates changed over security </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 NEW DELHI, Mar 14 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - The government raised fresh security concerns and asked the country's cricket board on Friday to revise match dates for the Indian Premier League (IPL) to avoid a clash of dates with the general election. The Ministry of Home Affairs said the league, planned from April 10 to May 24, would have to reschedule match dates for a second time because many regional governments had said they would find it tough to spare security forces who would be busy due to the poll, a month-long affair starting on April 16. Security concerns have shot up over the league, involving many international players, after gunmen attacked the Sri Lanka cricket team in Pakistan last week, injuring six players. Organisers of the multi-million dollar tournament have revised the schedule once to make sure matches were not taking place in cities on days they were going to the polls and local media reports said on Friday they would submit fresh dates for the ministry's clearance. "IPL organisers have been advised to accommodate the concerns of the various state governments and draw up a revised schedule and submit the same to the Ministry of Home Affairs," the ministry said in a statement. Gunmen attacked the Sri Lankan team bus in Lahore last week, killing seven Pakistanis in the ambush to trigger worldwide concerns sport could become a target of similar attacks. Last week Indian home minister P. Chidambaram said the country feared possible militant attacks during the election campaign. India remains nervous after Islamist militants killed 166 people in a strike on the financial hub Mumbai in Novem
